In a speech at a private residence in San Francisco, President Biden reflects on his time in the Oval Office and discusses the importance of democracy and the challenges facing America. He recounts the story of choosing the furniture for the office and talks about the portraits of past presidents, highlighting the significance of Franklin D. Roosevelt and Abraham Lincoln. Biden expresses his gratitude to his colleagues, including Vice President Kamala Harris and Secretary of the Interior Deb Haaland. He emphasizes the progress made during his administration, such as job creation, addressing climate change, and appointing the first Black woman to the Supreme Court. However, he also acknowledges the ongoing threats to democracy, including political violence and attempts to undermine institutions. Biden reaffirms his commitment to standing up against hate, protecting voting rights, and ensuring a better future for all Americans. He urges unity and calls on everyone to join together to save democracy and build a stronger, more inclusive nation.